card.desc:
So what is this tool? It's built on a service called "Trello". Trello is a tool for doing tasks on your own or with others. We've customized it for onboarding. 

For us, the main parts of Trello are:

- **boards.** This whole space you're looking at.
- **lists.** The labelled columns.
- **cards.** High level tasks which can be dragged between lists.
- **checklists.** These are great for smaller tasks within cards.

We've chosen to set up our Trello board so that there are a few lists:

- **To Do.** Tasks to accomplish.
- **In Progress.** A list for longer tasks you're currently working on.
- **Complete.** A list for dropping cards that you're done with.

The general idea is to drag cards from "To Do" through to "Completed".

## Why do we do this?

I bet you're asking this. As in, why don't we just use a document listing all the things to do?

That's a great question! 

Basically, we feel that this approach makes onboarding a more active and self-directed process. It also helps improve remote onboarding, which sometimes suffers compared to the personal in-person experience.

For example, with this workflow, a newcomer who needs help 3 days after arriving in the community, can drop a link to their personal Trello board into chat. A mature contributor (even if this is their first interaction with this person in their onboarding journey) can understand the _state of the newcomer's understanding_ -- what they know and where they are. The mature contributor is then better able to assist, without sussing out the answers to a whole ton of subtle questions about what the newcomer knows! :)
card.name: Read how this onboarding works

- **checklists.** These are great for smaller tasks within cards.

We've chosen to set up our Trello board so that there are a few lists:

- **To Do.** Tasks to accomplish.
- **In Progress.**. A list for longer tasks you're currently working on.
- **Complete.** A list for dropping cards that you're done with.

The general idea is to drag cards from "To Do" through to "Completed".

## Why do we do this?

I bet you're asking this. As in, why don't we just use a document listing all the things to do?

That's a great question!

Basically, we feel that this approach makes onboarding a more active and self-directed process. It also helps improve remote onboarding, which sometimes suffers compared to the personal experience of in-person onboarding. If a newcomer needs help 3 days after arriving in the community, they can drop a link to their personal Trello board into chat, and a mature contributor (even if this is their first interaction with them on their onboarding journey) can understand the "state of their brain" -- what they know and where they are. The mature contributor is then better able to assist, without sussing out the answers to a whole ton of subtle questions about what the newcomer knows! :)
